segments.text: And the modern Iran, at least the one that I'm acquainted with, dated back really to the former Shah's father, Reza Shah, who even though they say the Peacock Throne has existed for 2,000 years, something like that, his father was an illiterate sergeant and a cavalry.
They called it the Cossack.
It was based on the Russian Cossack.
And actually, I think he was up and from in the Azerbaijan area there.
And so he led the revolution that overthrew a very unpopular Shah.
He had no intention, supposedly, of becoming a Shah.
He was going to become a common leader.
Sort of like Jimmy Carter walking, you know, to the inauguration and that sort of thing.
But by public demand, they wanted him to become the shot.
So here you got a guy who's the illiterate sergeant, former sergeant, who becomes the leader of the nation.
He did have the ability with his down-to-earth leadership to appeal or to form a coalition, really, with all of the tribal leaders.
And in the tribe, if you've been in Iran, they have their own really governmental structure.
And he was able to pull all of them together to support the central government, which they hate.
They hate now.
They hate it in Korea.
They hate it in Vietnam.
Anywhere you go, out in the boondocks, they don't care about communism.
They won't be left alone, particularly in Iran.
So his only problem was that
He was a great admirer of Germany, and he had German advisors.
He was a great admirer of Hitler.
And so coming to World War II, the British had him move to South Africa, where he died.
But Shaw still was young.
But he was popular.
And Shaw then inherited the throne later on.
Of course, he was a tempest-made on his life.
It wounded him, but he wasn't.
It wasn't seriously wounded.
So he became a shot.
He was popular.
He was popular when we were there.
He was a good man.
He was highly trained.
He was an expert on military subjects worldwide, all about the British, our Army, Navy, Air Force, German, French.
He was a scholar of military operations.
He was schooled, of course, in Switzerland.
Also, he graduated with their own military academy.
And he was a good man.
He intended to modernize Iran, land reform, which he implemented, which made the rich people unhappy, and the Mullahs very unhappy.
But he accomplished it.
So they had this sort of a mutual, might have been kind of shaky, but a mutual coalition.
Of course, a coalition, that's redundant.
It would be mutual.
of all of the tribes around Iran.
And as we talked about, he had positioned a division or a brigade in the large population center, mainly recruited from the tribes.
And for a while, they had no problem, because all you have to do is tell the tribal leader that your quota is 200 young men, for example.
And they would produce them.
It's only when it starts getting, you lose the support of these tribes, then you have a time.
of getting your number of people.
So the Shah was very responsive, and he knew what our mission was.
We were paid, by the way, the mission by the Iranian government in addition to our own paycheck.
I paid a great big old check amount like this.
The military assistance group didn't get that.
So the Iranians then felt that we worked for them in a way.
So we were more than just visitors in the country.
We were actually...
which we couldn't be legally, but this was legal, it was approved, and the employment to a certain degree of the right.
And I enjoyed it very much.
We had several meetings with the Shah.
Could you describe him?
He was a very quiet individual, a very thoughtful individual.
As you noticed in interviews before he died, he usually would think, it wasn't that he didn't have a command of the English language, because of course he spoke British
English and not American English.
But what impressed me, as I already said, was his knowledge, military knowledge, of all weapons.
I don't mean he just had a speaking acquaintance with them, but he knew the character wisdom of the weapon, you know, the weight and all that sort of thing.
And so it
It wasn't just briefing him.
You'd sit down, and he would actually discuss, because each time we would go, and I would go with the general, because I was a G3, talking about what's proposed for the next year.
Even then, he'd ask for more, and then they could actually assimilate.
But that was the nature of that assignment, trying to get along politically with the Iranians, trying to train them.
Was communism a big fear?
Well, as you know, too, you could draw a circle around Tehran, about, say, 50, 100 kilometers around Tehran.
And that's really the seat.
That's where the power is.
Communism out in the provinces,
The Tudor party, for example, didn't exist.
It existed, though, in Tehran, because that's where it's important.
And it wasn't popular with Iranians until Mosaddegh, for example, who definitely was not a communist at all.
He was forced towards the Tudor party.
But Mosaddegh, first they blamed the British, and they kicked out the British.
After they nationalized the oil.
In 1951, they nationalized the British oil.
And they didn't think the Iranians could operate the refinery down at Abaddon and also the others.
But they did because the British, as they've done everywhere you know, as opposed to many other colonial powers, the British always trained the next echelon down.
If this guy was the head of department or the assistant was a local native,
So the British could move out and operate.
Now, they couldn't.
They couldn't over a long period of time as far as maintenance is concerned.
And that's where the Americans came in.
But they kicked out the British.
Mosaddegh had blamed all of the problems of the country on the British.
And you read newspaper articles now, and you are left impression in those particular times that the modulus was elected by popular vote, see?
And the Shah dissolved the Majlis and kicked out Mosaddegh because he was a tyrant, and he was unpopular.
They wanted to get rid of him.
And he, beginning right then, that's the reason we all hate the Shah, because that is when the Americans should not have supported the Shah.
They should have let him remain in Italy, and then we would have had democracy in Iran way back in 1951.
or 52 when actually most of that got kicked out.
That's not true.
He was very popular.
How do I know he's popular?
Not only by going around visiting, which I went all over Iran, but we used the Shah's train to go up to Bandershah up on the Caspian.
We wanted to go there because it was a picturesque trip.
The Scandinavian countries, I don't remember which one it was, might have been your ancestors.
engineers that carved out those tunnels, and they go up this mountain.
You can travel for about 30 minutes, and on the map, you haven't made any progress, just altitude.
You can look back down and see where you were 30 minutes before.
And then you go through the mountain, and you go on the other side, and you do the same thing to get across the mountain.
The people up and down had no idea that the Shah's train was coming along there.
Or was it the Shah?
Of course, I imagine the railroad.
clearing it, but I got the word out.
But because it was a Shah's train at the station where we stopped, people would come up with flowers to put on the train.
And how they got the word while we were sitting there, I don't know.
But of course, the Shah went there.
General McClure was there, and then McClure and Meany, and yours truly.
And so to me, that's not evidence of an unpopular individual at all.
Well, what about that charge about Mosaddegh and that it would have had so-called democracy back in 1951 or 1952?
What about that?
Mosaddegh didn't have any following nationwide.
He had some following in Tehran, but he was a good friend of our nation.
Ambassador Henderson
support him.
In fact, we're the ones who helped him escape.
Yeah.
You know him?
He's a real fine guy.
Yeah, he was ambassador at the time.
We helped him escape from his house when he was attacked and helped him get into hiding.
And so regardless of how the outcome would have been, the United States would still have been
friendly to that government.
It's not like Khomeini and all of that sort of thing.
Of course, I guess that's what good diplomacy is, when you have a favorable situation where regardless of which way the outcome.
But if the Shah hadn't returned, I think we would probably end up with a friction just like we have now.
But see, there wasn't a period of purging like Khomeini did.
See, anyone who's Western educated, and that's all you doctors and lawyers and you educate and so forth, they purge them.
They're either out of the country or in jail or dead.
So I really couldn't predict what would have happened then if Shaw hadn't returned.
But he didn't permanently leave.
He left, and it's true of the reports, I wasn't with CIA at that time.
I was later on, which we'll talk about.
But he left temporarily.
on our suggestion so that this overthrow could occur, which was really bloodless.
A few people got killed.
They shot up Mosaddegh's house with a tank.
Who engineered this overthrow?
General Bakhtiari, the same division commander that I was telling you about.
I should say he supported.
He provided the troops.
He was really occupying Tehran and getting Mossadegh out.
Nobody hurt Mossadegh.
It was very embarrassing to us.
I knew nothing about the CIA working.
You had to have funds and somebody that was working.
But the Iranian CIA, like a lot of people think, American goes in and he leads the charge.
Well, you don't.
It's all by contacts.
We were embarrassed, at least I was, because the best regimental commander we had in Tehran, he had the responsibility to put the security on Mosaddegh area.
So he discharged his responsibility.
And so it was his tanks that was defending Mosaddegh's house.
So he ended up by being arrested and put in prison, see, because he was doing what he was supposed to.
He didn't stay there very long.
But he was doing exactly what he was supposed to do, and he was doing a good job.
But that was earlier.
The only bloodshed was the exchange between this colonel's forces and General Bakhtiari's forces.
So the Shah was in Rome.
He came back.
I guess a lot of people out in the province didn't even know anything like this happened.
Of course, a number of people in the United States recently charged that the CIA really engineered the overthrow.
and brought the shawl back.
Well, that's true.
That's true.
It would never have occurred if CIA hadn't been involved in it.
Well, what specifically was their involvement?
Well, they provided the money and the contacts and the assurance that the United States would support Bakhtiar if he overthrew, well, much overthrowing, just getting rid of Mozadegh.

Because the modules wasn't properly elected, half of them were appointed by the shahs, and the other half, like the lower and the higher house that we have, they were so-called elected, but even they were more appointed.
They've had an election here recently.
I mean, those people actually voted.
But this other way that...
What was your opinion toward this interference in another country's internal affairs?
Well, I think it was the best interest of the United States for the Shah to continue to be, because I'm sure that that country would have gone communistic because the Tudor party was gaining control.
That's the reason why they had to overthrow the government.
Vostok had to turn to the Tudors.
That was the only one he had left.
And the USSR thought, this is it now.
We're going to get Iran.
Because who is going to stand between us then?
Do you remember what Ambassador Henderson had to do, what the ONZ had to do with this?
Oh, he'd have to have complete knowledge.
You couldn't go in and operate without him.
We had members of the CIA.
In fact, a friend of mine I didn't know at the time was on this.
Ambassador Henderson's staff, he's a military type.
He was there as a civilian.
He was a contact, in other words, between Henderson and the CIA.
And also, the faction also used in that was a, Tehran has athletic clubs that are very popular.
You know, the old ancient, really some art more than anything else.
And the Shah is a member of that.
Of course, he heads all of them.
So they were all pro-Shah.
The country was pro-Shah.
There's no question in my mind.
People are trying to rewrite history and judge the Shah later, like, with what occurred then.
It's just no comparison at all.
Why do you think the Shah seemed to lose popularity over the next generation?
You mean...
Yeah, why do you think that if you think he was popular in the early 50s, why was he so unpopular by the late 1970s?
I think we contributed, the United States contributed to that.
When we were there, it was only internal security, see, those were the forces.
Later on, and of course he's modernized, things were getting better there.
But I think what really
contributed most to his downfall is when the United States says, now we're going to look to you to be the strong man in the Middle East.
No longer we expect you to maintain internal security.
Obviously, you can do that.
But we need someone who can sort of be the peace enforcer in the area, suggesting that perhaps you get modern aircraft and modern Navy, which they did.
did have, then you would be in a position to utilize this force if needed in other parts of the Middle East.
But mainly, you would be a deterrent, being strong, that no one would perhaps attack, say, in Saudi Arabia or Iraq.
Of course, Iraq was always the last people when we were there.
They were leaning towards the USSR.
But it's no doubt in my mind that Mossadegh was forced to turn to the Tudor party, and he would never have been able to turn loose of that tiger that he had to the tail.
Now, one might say, well, maybe that would have been better, but it wouldn't, because the USSR would be on down the Persian Gulf.
They'd have a puppet government there, just like they try to have in Afghanistan.
See, all they have to do, they have a treaty with them now.
All they have to do is to say, help.
I think that goes back to 1921, isn't it?
You're the expert on history.
And some are fearsome now that this may occur.
The USSR said, well, we're invited to come down.
They needed our security.
Turmoil, anarchy.
The government existed to ask for help.
What about the internal security, the whole idea of internal security over the last 25 years?
Many people have charged at the Shaw, built up the secret forces, secret service forces, and then started to torture people, and you've heard it all.
And I was wondering about our role back in the early 1950s as far as helping him set up internal security and if we knew any of this torture was going on.
No.
Not when I was there, because they hadn't advanced to that point.
See, we didn't even have advisors in the field, I think.
We were all in Tehran.
And when you say we, how many were there?
Oh, I guess our mission there, we had about 30, and I guess there were about 10 others in the MAG, the Military Assistance Group.
That includes officers and non-commissioned officers.
And so the training all was occurring in the Tehran area.
Those would come from the province and would come in to school that we established.
And we were just getting them established.
We were also sending officers to the United States.
And you had two factions in the armed forces.
Previously, they had been going to France to school.
French was the second language.
They went into English also.
But a lot of them didn't speak English.
So then, before they go to the United States,
of course, speak English.
And there were a lot of, a lot of them were resentful of Americans because they didn't like the British.
Of course, they, English speaking, and here we come in.
And they sort of identified us with the British rather than France.
But, now the other thing besides this building up to Shaw, this tremendous American population had moved in there.
Yeah.
Now, they even resented us when we were there in small numbers.
See?
Do you have any examples of resentment?
Well, you know, we provided transportation.
Our government did.
We had Chevrolet sedans and had license, Iranian license plates on them.
And so one day, my driver was sitting waiting, and this Iranian officer came up and says,
I'm taking over this car.
I want to go somewhere.
He said, but you can't.
This is Colonel Andrews' car.
He said, I don't care.
So he forced the driver to drive it off, of course, in the report.
He thought that was an Iranian car.
He thought their government had bought this car for us, which it wasn't.
It was our own car.
And they just resented us having a sedan, and they rode around in Jeeps.
That's one example.
Now, what about this thing about internal security?
We really didn't help as far as building up this police force.
You're talking about Savick, huh?
Yeah.
One other, by the way, after Mosaddegh was overthrown, there were plans that were found for the assassination of America.
Of Americans?
Yeah.
Us, we lived up at Tajri Circle, for example, and the plan was how they were going to take care of us.
And, of course, we had vehicles we kept there.
We had an evacuation plan for if we had to get to Tehran Air Base to be evacuated.
So not only do I say that if it didn't turn out successful, even though Loy Henderson was being very friendly with Mossadegh, something might have happened to the American population that
that were there.
And I'm sure the USSR, just like we had CIA, they also operating in there.
And they probably would desire to have some Americans killed, because that would indicate that Ronnie was unhappy with them, and they were unwelcome.
They shouldn't have ever been there.
But they had, of course, a security force, clandestine, no doubt, that we were there.
But I wasn't aware.
because I wasn't around the country of any other people put in jail.
Now, the Iranians, they mistreated the troops.
They'd slap them and kick them.
And even at that time, they could denounce somebody, and they wouldn't have a trial.
They'd go put them in, and they'd stay in there for weeks and months, just like they're doing now, except now they're killing them.
In other words, the same Iranians, what they're doing now, were Iranians, what they were doing then.
The other was the Shah's force.
Now, at least the Shah never did say, go out and kill these people.
He claims he wasn't even aware if it was, and I don't think he was.
But he's responsible because his people did it.
But they're brutal as long as they have the upper hand.
And they like to have turmoil.
Even when we were there, they'd say, let's go down to the bazaar and have a shalook.
A shalook there, you know, it was marching and yelling, waving their hands, yelling slogans.
And they push each other.
They call that a chaluk, you know, organ and all that sort of thing.
In fact, we even had an Iranian officer told me one time he didn't want to fly with the Iranian pilots because the landing and takeoff is a chaluk.
They even disagree on what they're doing on getting the gear up and landing.
He said, I'm going to go fly with them.
No, they like chalukes.
That's the reason you see them all.
And then you give them a TV camera.
They really like to demonstrate.
They all want to be martyrs.
You know, they beat themselves.
Yet they take animal blood and put it all over them, you know, and beat as if, boy, they beat themselves and they're just bleeding all over.
When they have a technique where they hit here instead of the chain, you know, hit there.
Very emotional people, I think.
Difficult to really understand.
Tell me about Lloyd Henderson.
What type of man was he?
A real...
I think a model diplomat, soft-spoken ability.
He told us one day, he says he was laughing because the USSR just experienced a setback.
I think the Iranians kicked out one of their diplomats there.
And he laughed and he said, the secret weapon the Iranians have that the USSR just can't figure them out.
Well, everything I've been discussing, nobody else can really figure them out because they're unpredictable.
The Shah wasn't unpredictable.
That's the reason I think he was a real stabilizing force.
He was popular.
But when he got all of this equipment, brought in all of these Americans, and they set up their own community,
and ignored the Iranians, except the rich, wealthy Iranians.
They had resentment.
That should never happen, but he had to do that.
You bring all this sophisticated equipment, Iranians can't operate.
Now, you said before that you were later with the CIA.
Was that in Iran?
No.
I'd like to leave in Iran.
And I didn't even know my friend was a CIA until I joined the CIA.
Where it says support group on that thing, that's a cover for CIA.
Oh, okay.
Were you happy to leave Iran in 1954?
Well, after two years, yeah.
My wife Mimi had a couple of operations.
Of course, she had to leave Iran and go to Germany to do that.
About two years.
I had a lot of Iranian friends, and we enjoyed it very much.
Very frustrating.
Why?
Trying to get things accomplished.
You know, Americans, I also want to read Americans were unpopular with some of the Iranians because we were impatient.
You know, Americans want to do things and get it done.
They want to be able to mark your progress and have a chart up there.
And I think we made some progress, but not near what you would expect in two years.
We established schools.
We couldn't get the Iranians to agree to set up an officer candidate school.
Yet their military academy, just like ours, could not produce sufficient officers.
So many of the units were understaffed with officers.
And they didn't want warrant officers.
And their argument was, if you have warrant officers,
Officer candidates, they had third lieutenants there.
Said if you make them third lieutenants, they'll want to get promoted like everybody else.
And they wanted them to remain a second-class citizen.
They would deal with them or view them as just a sergeant with officer rank.
Yet, when you send them to school,
They're more knowledgeable than the so-called military academy drivers.
So they're even jealous of each other.
It sounds to me like this is a tremendous problem of two different cultures not being able to understand each other.
Is that right?
Yeah, you could probably say that.
Now we've got them educated in the United States, and they come back.
They'd be an entirely different person.
They then were your close friends.
They felt closer to you than they were on you.
Let me give you another example.
We sent a lot to Fort Sam Houston here, to the Brook Medical Center, to take medical specialists, a little bit more than medical aid men, but at least they were laboratory people.
They'd come back.
They'd hang up a shingle, go into practice, call themselves doctor and operator.
Now, I'll tell you another example.
Many of them didn't want to come back and didn't come back.
They'd come back.
They'd remain over here.
One day, we were looking for an individual who had been over here to medical school, to specialist training, not in the medical school.
And it's traced him down.
Of course, we use the FBI here in this country to locate these people.
And their embassy wanted to find him, the Iranian embassy.
And they found this individual of all places.
He was a resident in Mayo's clinic.
Mayo's clinic?
Yeah.
He convinced him, he was an exchange student, you know, that he had finished medical school, and now he was time for his residency.
And they didn't take the time, you know, they looked at all his papers, and of course they do have him, have him right.
And he was there, and they said he was doing a pretty good job, but man, he was practicing medicine in the hospital, in a big hospital.
So then it stopped all of that, of course.
It went out to all of the hospitals where they really had to be sure they documented it.
So I'm not surprised that our Iranian students here, they act just like Iranians.
Here at the university now, they have demonstrations now, pro-Komanian, anti-Komanian.
And yell insults, shalooking at each other.
And get mad at the Americans, because we won't take sides.
The students there say, to hell with you.
Why don't all of you go back?
Now, they aren't pro-Shah.
I don't mean to say that.
They're against Komanian.
I guess there'd be some of them in Alpha Bandar songs.
Well, you want to move on to another country?
This is really fantastic.
It appears to me that this seems that this is a very frustrating assignment for you.
Yeah, I want to tell you.
Well, I enjoyed it because it was a challenge, but yeah, it's frustrating.
It kind of gives you ulcers, you know.
But fortunately, we all do, and my commanding general there is a bit
We're all in it together and doing the best we can.
Well, Zimmerman first and then McClure, General McClure.
I want to tell you one other thing so you better understand that, at least on the ground.
Everything is done in Iran involves Bakshis.
Now, just like in the Far East, it would be Kamsha, you know, but Bakshi.
Now, Americans might call it TIPS.
And the lawyer might call it a bribe.
And this is where we've tied the hands of industry here in our nation because we can no longer pay these fees, which is really bocce.
But that's the way they do business.
Now, when we first arrived there, there's a policeman up at Tawdry Circle.
And you say, well, then our house was right there.
It would be safe.
Now, it's only safe if you do this.
You go to this policeman and you say, now, I live here and it's very important that I don't get robbed.
Now, I know that you are really an outstanding enforcer of the law and nothing like this would happen with you here on your post.
But for me to show my appreciation of your high standard of law enforcement, I'm going to give you each month
This Bakshi's here.
Of course, he's got his hand out at all times when he gets it.
Now, he keeps the crooks away from our house because they're all organized.
Now, if I didn't do that, the crooks come to him and he gives him Bakshi.
And he'll tell him the hours we keep, everything about it.
Do they have a dog?
and then you get robbed, see?
Also, of course, in their religion, just like in Saudi Arabia where they cut off hands and legs and so forth, there it's not only against the law, but it's against their religion.
But they rationalize that.
They view them as being like Robin Hood, sort of an honor among thieves.
We will only steal from the wealthy, those who have rather than wealthy.
And we will leave all you poor folks alone.
So they say, well, we don't have much.
Al has not been kind to us.
Why shouldn't he?
Of course, all Americans were hunk of sugar as they have ever were.
We were all wealthy, see.
But we never got robbed, because I had sense enough to learn when I got there.
He got degrees of Palmer.
Now, that's a bribe.
But maybe it's a tip, because he makes so little money.
And do you remember how much it was a month?
No, I think it's equivalent of about
$5 or something like that, which was a lot of money there at that time.
And they have a thieves market then.
I don't know what they have now.
And I mean a real thieves market.
Here, you know, it's a joke.
You go buy secondhand goods and so forth, and they call it a thieves market.
They steal your hubcaps, even maybe your tires if you don't have them guarded and locked up.
You don't dare park your car out in the street overnight.
If the car is still there, it'll be stripped.
But if you'll hurry and go down to the thieves market, you can buy back all this equipment at really a good price.
They'll make you a good deal on this thing.
And you go to the police and you say, but they stole it and I found it down there.
Well, first, he doesn't understand the language.
He doesn't know what you're talking about.
And you say, well, I've got my mark on this tire here.
He says, yeah, over here.
You finally get an interpreter.
What did he say?
He says, a lot of tires have marks like that.
How do I know that's his mark?
So they're all involved with that, too.
But you'd rather buy it and get it back at a good bargain price.
And they all know that.
That's the way they operate.
You can call it dual standard or back.
But if you don't understand all of that, another thing, you can go to an individual, and you say, I need this.
Oil and stove, for example.
But you're wasting your time if you try to go down and shop.
But you tell him how much you want to pay.
Mr. Maynard was our great contact man.
He could get you reals at a rate that you couldn't get at the bank or anywhere else.
He could get you a stove cheaper than you can get anywhere else.
And he could expedite it.
But that's the way to do business.
Everything's bordered.
And they do steal from the wealthier runners, just like they do from Americans.
I'll tell you one more on this, and then we'll move on to another thing.
We were telling about, one of our Americans got robbed, and I was telling the minister of defense, we were at a party, about this.
He said, we got robbed?
I said, really?
I wouldn't think you people would go.
Oh, yes.
He said, just the other night.
And they lived just like we had.
It's a compound with a big high fence.
And, of course, you ring the bell outside, and surely a servant comes and answers that during the day.
And the servants and the rich people live in the back.
And, of course, you lock the doors in the big houses.
We didn't have an overnight servant.
We had a woman who worked for us during the daytime and had a yard man to take care of the yard and the garden.
But he said just the other night,
I was, we were in bed, and I heard a pounding on my door.
See, they'd already gotten over the fence.
They didn't ring the bell out at the door, at the gate.
And he said, I went to the door and opened it, and I said, what are you doing beating on my door this time of the night?
He said, I beg your pardon, I apologize.
Well, who are you?
He said, I'm a thief.
I have come to rob you.
Well, why are you beating on the door if you're going to rob me?
He said, because I need your help, because my partner has fallen in your well, and I can't get him out.
So he said, okay.
So he went and helped this guy get his partner out of the well.
I guess they reinforced a rope or something, and they got him out.
And he just bowed and thanked him very much.
He said, thank you very much for helping us out.
We won't rob you.
So he says, goodbye, thief.
So he went his way.
Well, we left Iran and we went to the Armed Forces Staff College.
Yeah, okay, 1955.
And I was hopeful I'd go to the Army War College.
Unless you did later.
